article.description: Katie Smith scored 22 points to help the Lynx snap a two-game losing streak with a 66-58 victory over the Comets on Saturday night.
article.headline: Swoopes, slowed by sore ankle, scores 18
article.linkText: Smith, Lynx beat up on short-handed Comets
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Katie Smith and the Minnesota Lynx took an
aggressive approach against the tired Houston Comets.

Smith scored 22 points to help the Lynx snap a two-game losing
streak with a 66-58 victory Saturday night.

"There was a different mentality and a different attitude about
the team," Minnesota coach Suzie McConnell Serio said. "We came
out with more enthusiasm and more energy and were able to dictate
the tempo right from the beginning."

Tamika Williams added 12 points and 11 rebounds for the Lynx
(5-5). Sheryl Swoopes, slowed by a sore right ankle, led the Comets
(6-6) with 18 points, and Michelle Snow had 14.

It was the second loss in two nights for the Comets, prompting
coach Van Chancellor to keep the team behind closed doors for an
extended postgame meeting.

"They beat us from start to finish," Chancellor said. "We're
not very good at this time, and Minnesota outplayed us. Give them
all the credit."

Minnesota led by as many as nine points in the first half on the
strength of Smith's 10 points, but Houston scored the final six
points of the half to pull within three.

Houston cut Minnesota's lead to a point early in the second half
before the Lynx pulled away.
